Classification Functions

LRclassifyShort = function(waveseq)
{
  maxInd = which.max(waveseq)
  minInd = which.min(waveseq)
  
  maxVal = waveseq[maxInd]
  minVal = waveseq[minInd]
  
  call = ifelse(abs(maxVal) > abs(minVal), "R", "L")
  
  return(call)
}

LRclassifyMed = function(waveseq)
{
  maxInd = which.max(waveseq) ## the position of the maximum value
  minInd = which.min(waveseq) ## the position of the minimum value
  
  call = ifelse(maxInd < minInd, "R", "L")
  
  return(call)
}
Description of classification function:
1. For short waves: The classifier finds the  min and max value for current
window and returns R or L based on if the abs(maxVal) is greater
than abs(minVal) or vice-versa.

2. For medium/long waves: The classifier finds the position of min and max for current
window and returns R or L based on if the maxInd is less than
minInd or vice-versa.

Event Identification Section

identify_event <- function(Y,  xtime, 
                                windowSize = 1, 
                                thresholdEvents = 650,
                                downSampleRate = 20) {
  
   
    x = max(xtime) - windowSize
    indexLastWindow = max(which(xtime <= x)) + 1
    ind = seq(1, indexLastWindow, by = downSampleRate)

    
    timeMiddle <- xtime[ind] + windowSize/2 
    testStat = rep(NA, length(ind))
  
    
    for (i in 1:length(ind)) {
        Y_subset <- Y[xtime >= xtime[ind[i]] & xtime < xtime[ind[i]] + windowSize]
       testStat[i] <-  sd(Y_subset)
  }
  
    
    predictedEvent <- which(testStat > thresholdEvents)
    eventTimes <- timeMiddle[predictedEvent] 
  
   
    gaps <- which(diff(eventTimes) > mean(diff(eventTimes)))
    noiseInterval <- rbind(
                c(range(xtime)[1], min(eventTimes)),
                cbind(eventTimes[gaps], eventTimes[gaps+1]),
                c(max(eventTimes), range(xtime)[2])
                )
    
    eventsInterval <- cbind(noiseInterval[-nrow(noiseInterval),2], 
                            noiseInterval[-1,1])
    
    return(list(num_event = length(gaps) + 1, 
           predictedNoiseInterval = noiseInterval,
           predictedEventInterval = eventsInterval))
}
This function is used to identify events while streaming/reading input.
It is based on the standard deviation values of the current window.

Function to extract signal

extractSignal = function(limits, seq, xtime)
{
    index = (xtime > limits[1]) & (xtime < limits[2])
    return(seq[index])
}
This function is used later and was taken from the Lab Sample Code.

Predictions for Short Files

classifier_outcomes_short = list()

for (file in 1:24){
  current_wave = files_short_streaming[[file]]
  Y = current_wave@left
  xtime = seq_len(length(current_wave))/current_wave@samp.rate
  Eventresult = list()
  Eventresult = identify_event(Y, xtime, windowSize = 0.55, downSampleRate = 30, thresholdEvents = 300)
  
  event_type <- c()
  for(i in 1:nrow(Eventresult$predictedEventInterval)) {
      vari <- LRclassifyShort(Y[(Eventresult$predictedEventInterval[i, 1] * 10000) : (Eventresult$predictedEventInterval[i, 2] *
             10000)])
      event_type <- c(event_type, vari)
    }
  
  classifier_outcomes_short[file] = stri_paste(event_type, collapse='')

}
The above code chunk runs our classifier on short files and stores the predicted
labels in a new list variable, this will be used later to find accuracy.

Answer 2a

Build SVM and Give Accuracy

## quick filter to reduce computational time
largevar = apply(gse, 1, sd)
largevar = largevar * largevar
ind = which(largevar > quantile(largevar, 0.95))

X = as.matrix(t(exprs(gse[ind,])))
y = gse$Outcome
cvK = 4  # number of CV folds
cv_acc_svm  = c()



  cvSets = cvTools::cvFolds(nrow(X), cvK)  # permute all the data, into 5 folds
  cv_acc_svm =c()
  lrm_fits = c()
  for (j in 1:cvK) {
    test_id = cvSets$subsets[cvSets$which == j]
    X_test = X[test_id, ]
    X_train = X[-test_id, ]
    y_test = y[test_id]
    y_train = y[-test_id]
    
    
    ## SVM
    svm_res <- e1071::svm(x = X_train, y = as.factor(y_train))
    fit <- predict(svm_res, X_test)
    lrm_fits = append(lrm_fits, fit)
    cv_acc_svm[j] = mean(fit == y_test)

  }

print("Accuracy of the SVM model is: ")
## [1] "Accuracy of the SVM model is: "
print(mean(cv_acc_svm))
## [1] 0.6
lrm_fits = as.data.frame(lrm_fits)
The code above undertakes pre-validation and SVM training.
It also prints the mean accuracy of the svm model.

Classify coral bleaching and find distribution

reef_data$variance = ifelse(reef_data$SSTA_Standard_Deviation < 0.80, "Low", "High")
boxplot(reef_data$Average_bleaching ~ reef_data$variance, ylim= c(0, 4), ylab = "Average Bleaching", xlab = "Variance")

As we can see from the boxplot, the distribution for the group with high 
SSTA standard deviation is towards the lower end when compared to the boxplot for the group with low SSTA standard deviation. Further more the difference in Quantile values is evident for the box plots.
The next code chunk carries out a t-test to see if the difference is significant.
